istorical work on the late Habsburg Monarchy has focused primarily on national movements and ethnic conflicts, with the result that too little attention has been devoted to the state and ruling dynasty. This volume is the first of its kind to concentrate on attempts by the imperial government to generate a dynastic-oriented state patriotism in the multinational Habsburg Monarchy. It examines those forces in state and society which tended toward the promotion of state unity and loyalty towards the ruling house. These essays, all original contributions and written by an international group of historians, provide a critical examination of the phenomenon of “dynastic patriotism” and offer a richly nuanced treatment of the multinational empire in its final phase.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aGroup identityzAustria. 0aNationalismzAustria. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Austria & Hungary.2bisacsh1 aBruckmüller, Ernst, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCole, Laurence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCole, Laurence, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEvans, R. J. W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreifeld, Alice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKent, Sarah A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeCaine Agnew, Hugh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRachamimov, Alon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUnowsky, Daniel L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUnowsky, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWingfield, Nancy M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWolf, Chr